column168: Schenker, Inc Richmnd,VA received a shipment from Dynamic Aviation for transport to Botswana.  Shipment did not contain any dangerous goods markings on the out side of the carton.  The shipper did not declare on any of the documents provided that the shipment contain oxygen compressed. Shipper marked NO Hazardous Materials were contained in this shipment on the Scheker Shippers Letter of Instruction. The Schenker Richmond, VA. office transfered this shipment by truck to our JFK office for consolidation to Botswana.  Schenker JFK office preformed ETD cargo screening on this shipment and received a postive alarm. To resolve this alarm, Schenker JFK opened this shipment to inspect and found  two undeclared  tanks labeled oxygen Gas No Inflamable 2 and Oxidante. ONU1072.  The tanks appear not to be empty and appear to contain gas.
column169: Schenker, Inc will not accept any new shipments from Dynamic Aviation. At this time Schenker, Inc has  blocked any new shipments from being entered in our computer system.

column168: A California P.U.C./FRA transportation/hazardous material inspector reported finding tank car DBUX 301941 emanating residue product vapors/odor from its manway closure during inspections in the railyard. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected DBUX 301941 finding all manway securement bolts tool tight. Detailed inspection of the installed manway gasket revealed that the gasket was compressed and not sealing properly. Responders replaced the manway gasket in kind and resecured the manway cover by 1350 hrs. PDT, 11/02/2011, thus eliminating further product vapors/odor. Intact seals removed identified as BP West Coast 0009390 and 0009389 were replaced by BNSF seals numbered 06157136 and 06157134.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

Responders installed a new manway gasket and properly secured all manway securement bolts on the manway cover by 2030 hrs. PDT, 11/03/2011. On Saturday, 11/12/2011 at 2300 hours PTRA Trainmaster was notified that tank car GATX 17711, loaded combustible liquid, was observed leaking from the manway area when the car was switched. The car was in PTRA American Yard. Inspection found that the product was isolated on the sides of the tank car, no ground contamination was observed. The car was moved into track 201 where it could be inspected and repaired. On 11/13/2011 M&M Protection was called to remediate the product on the sides of the tank and inspect the manway.  Upon inspection it was determined that the manway gasket was not installed prior to sealing the car. There was an old damaged  gasket laying on top of the tank car. M&M installed a new gasket and sealed the car. Product was pressure washed off of the car using a water based solution of micro bugs (pure green). The area was cleared at 1045 hours on 11/13. Chemtrec was notified of the incident and could not find the shipper, JW Stone Oil Distributors, in their system. The seal on the tank car should Murphy Oil out of Superior, Wisconsin was the party that loaded the tank. Chemtrec was attempting to notify Murphy Oil of the incident and subsequent remediation and repairs.
column169: FRA Haz Mat inspectors have been notified of this incident as this is the second issue with Murphy Oil cars on the PTRA.

column168: The shipment from North State Aviation was received at approximately 15:45 on Wednesday, November 09. When the box was opened, the time-sensitive fuses were unpacked and processed for reshipping to Delta Airlines. Thursday morning, November 10, when the remainder of the contents of the box was removed, a single battery pack for an Electronic Locating Transponder (ELT) was removed. It was packed in a mylar anti-static envelope. The used and expired battery pack contained 6 lithium batteries hooked up in a series that had been removed from a Miami Air aircraft. There was no indication of HazMat (lable) on the outside of the box, the shipping paperwork did not state HazMat inside of the box, and the invoice just stated "battery pack." There was no other paperwork included with this shipment. The shipper was notified by Mr. Tom Ostendorp, Vise President of Maintenance.       At approximately 16:00 on Thursday, the local FAA HazMat office was called (305-716-3340) and a voice message was left. The following day, Friday at approximately 09:15, another voice message was left at the same number. Also the Regional FAA HazMat office in Atlanta (404-305-6831) was called and a voice massage left.     Monday morning, November 14, I received a call from Mr. John Barrett in Atlanta and from Special Agent Ms. Danielle Rezendes from the local Miami FAA Security and Hazardous Materials office. Ms. Rezendes stopped by the Miami Air hangar at approximately 10:45 to take pictures of the battery pack and statements from the employee who unpacked the contents of the shipment. Copies of all available paperwork was provided to Ms. Rezendes.
column169: Shipper advised of unreported hazmat shipment.

The valve was properly closed and the plug made tool tight stopping the release.

column169: Loader opened the trailer to start unloading it when it arrived from Spokane.  Loader noticed the bottom of one of the cartons was wet on the bottom. column168: Trailer arrived at Con-way facility in Henderson, Co.  Hostler opened the door to bring trailer up to the dock and immediately smelled an ammonia odor coming from the trailer.  Supervisor contacted Chemtrec who advised they could not assist unless supervisor was able to see the material/packaging that was spilled.  Supervisor contacted Linehaul Safety and spoke with CGO Safety Coordinator as well as Safety Manager.  It was determined the safest measure to ensure no injury to employees was to have Belfor Enviornmental come to clean up.  Trailer isolated until arrival.  Belfor advised tote bin bunges needed to be tightened and that this was a shipper error.

column168: During an outbound train inspection in the railyard, tank car GATX 80573 was reported with fresh product on its side shell that emanated from GATX 80573's manway closure. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspected GATX 80573 finding three manway securement bolts not applied and the remaining three bolts less than tool tight. No ground impact from product spillage was reported. Further inspection revealed the manway gasket was in place and in serviceable condition. All top operating valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. Responder properly applied and tool tightened all manway securement bolts.  No shipper seals were affixed at the manway or the valve housing cover. Seals BNSF 06157414 and BNSF 06157404 were applied to the manway and valve housing cover respectively. GATX 80573 was moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting cleansing of tank shell spillage. Contractors steamed cleaned the product spillage off GATX 80573's tank shell during the morning hours of 11/14/2011.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing; Threaded Connection
column168: An Aurora Cooperative employee was delivering 2 anhydrous ammonia nurse trailers to a farmer; when at approximately 1240 hrs. on November 9, 2011; the right front axle spindle of the first trailer broke, causing the wheel to come off, allowing the right front axle end to drop to the road surface.  This end of the right front axle then dug into the soft turf of the right shoulder of the roadway causing the first nurse trailer to flip over and roll on the tank into the road ditch.  The second trailer followed into the ditch, remaining upright with only minor damage to the trailer tongue and no damage to the tank.      During the rollover, when the protection device for the 3/4" pressure relief valve contacted the ground, it bent; allowing the pressure relief valve to also contact the ground, resulting in a 1/4” long crack in a pipe thread at the base of the valve.  Liquid ammonia also surged out of the pressure relief valve, with the valve failing to reclose entirely.  The tank came to rest on its left side, releasing liquid ammonia from the cracked pipe thread and the 3/4” pressure relief valve.  The liquid ammonia immediately vaporized with the help of the NW 25 to 30 mph winds and the 50°F temperature.  At approximately 1345 hrs., using a front end loader, the nurse tank was set upright and the leak then stopped.    The remaining product was transferred to another nurse trailer, emptying the damaged nurse tank.  Duration of the release was approximately 65 minutes.  With the high winds and favorable temperatures, all released product completely dissipated into the air.
column169: It has been determined the failure of the axle spindle was the root cause of this incident.  To prevent reoccurrence, heavier axle spindles are being installed on these nurse trailers’ running gears.  Where possible; additional support will be incorporated into the pressure relief valve’s rollover protection devices.

The Ross Express driver loaded the 4 - HIM drums of Potassium Hydroxide @ Univar USA in Salem, MA and secured the drums in the trailer with a nylon strap to the trailer wall. When he arrived at his next customer in Ipswich, MA, he noticed the load securement strap had fallen off the drums causing one of the 4 drums to move and be damaged. The drum that leaked product was on its side in the back of his trailer with the cut on the side up where the drum sat in the trailer. Some product had leaking onto the trailer floor. The estimated product loss from the drum was approx.- 4 gallons from the 55 gallon container once he was able to do a temporary repair. He was able to uses and to absorb the spill in the trailer. After he was able to return to the Sutton, MA terminal, the trailer was placed out of service and left to ventilate and a neutralizing product was used against the remaining H/M product in the wood floor. The disposal of the drum with remaining product and the neutralized H/M product will be disposed through New England Disposal Technologies, Inc. 83 Gilmore Drive, Sutton, MA.
column169: Driver needs to use the load securement strap properly to the e-track to have secured drums. Ross driver has been given H/M training on 1/12/2009 & 10/3/2011 to be able to implement our company procedures with regard to company H/M spill response procedures. He was able to follow instruction from Ross Express's MA terminal manager to protect himself first and then keep anyone away from H/M spill location. He was instructed to get his bill of lading, notify the terminal manager what the H/M product leaking was and to what extent the leak was. He then was told to use his emergency response guidebook to be able to be on the same page as the terminal manager. The guide page number was 154. After this spill evaluation our employee was able to do a temporary repair safely. Proper load securement was made to all the drums in the back of his trailer including the repaired damaged drum.The drum then placed in a containment drum at the MA terminal preparing for its disposal with the spilled material/sand.

A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was being unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility for consolidation into another trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.  While unloading with a forklift, the edge of a pallet came in contact with the valve on the 250 gallon IBC tote, bending the valve and causing a small fracture.  A small pail was placed under the leaking valve.  The appropriate personal protecive equipment was donned and an absorbent material was used to clean up the leak from the trailer floor.  The remaining liquid was transferred to a 55 gallon poly drum along with the cleanup material.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The person unloading with the forklift was cautioned to use better care when operating in close proximity to other containers.

DURING AN EXAMINATION OF THE NOTES PREPARED DURING THE HAZMAT CLEAN-UP PROCESS, THE UPS HAZMAT ASSOCIATE NOTICED THAT THE BATTERY WAS AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT, SINCE THE OUTER CARTON HAD NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR DESIGNATIONS, YET THE INTERNAL BATTERY CONTAINED A CLASS 8 CORROSIVE HAZMAT DIAMOND LABEL AND A UN#2794, AND THEREFORE THEY CONTACTED THE UPS HAZMAT SUPPORT CENTER.

TWO 1 GALLON CANS LAYING ON SIDE IN A REUSED BOX WITH NO EXTERNAL MARKINGS OR LABELS. UPON INSPECTION OF PACKING LIST CONTENTS WERE FOUND AND VERIFIED UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE TO BE WELDON 2007. PACKING SLIP ALSO IDENTIFIED THAT FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL SHOULD HAVE BEEN APPLIED.

The box was found in the sort with frost on two sides of the box. I opened the box to reveal a food stuff (rice balls) being kept cold by two chunks of dry ice. There were no markings, labeling, shipping papers, emergency response information nor other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated. I called the FAA, and spoke to Hazmat Mgr Drew Stabala. Mgr Strabala asked me to take pictures of the shipment. I took pictures of the contents, Dry Ice, and six sides of the package. The freight was released to the shipper on Friday, 11/4/11.

column168: Tank car GATX 200601 was reported in the railyard leaking product from the top valve fitting area. The closure plug was tool tightened by the responder and the valve handle moved to the full closed position, which ended the product release by 0500 hrs. PST, 11/12/2011.  All spillage evaporated and no ground impact from spillage was observed. Intact seal NOVA 11925 at the valve housing cover was replaced by seal BNSF 06157624.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column25: Centennial Energy LLC by Red River Supply Inc.
column168: Tank car NATX 37037 was reported with fresh product on its side shell that emanated from the top valve fitting area. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected NATX 37037 removing intact shipper seal numbered 1271074 0003235 from valve housing cover. The responder observed the leak source at the base of the threaded 3 inch stainless steel closed liquid ball valve. This liquid valve appeared to be newly installed (likely installed when NATX 37037 completed its tank qualification in 2011). The responder tool tightened this valve on its threaded connection ending further leakage.  No ground impact from spillage was noted.  NATX 37037 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard for a detailed liquid valve inspection and cleaning of the spillage from its tank shell.   On 11/15/2011, contract responders removed and inspected the liquid valve's threaded connections. The responders reported no thread sealant applied on the liquid lines 2 inch threaded pipe nipple. Also, a 3 inch threaded bushing fitted on the 2 inch pipe nipple had little thread sealant applied.  The responders applied Teflon tape and thread sealant on all threaded connections. The 3 inch bushing was secured on the pipe nipple and the liquid valve was re-installed and properly tool tightened. Spillage on the tank shell was treated with a degreasing solution and then wiped. Seal numbered 2877112 was applied onto the valve housing cover.    The shipper was contacted and applied for a FRA OTMA for continued rail transportation of NATX 37037.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On 11/7/2011 at 0150 hrs, personnel in the CSXT Parkersburg, WV yard discovered GATX 93335, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the top of the tank car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Arkema Inc., was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2011-11-07-00004. SPSI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a Salco rupture disk assembly with the top assembly off and the rupture disk out of place. The surge protection was found on top of the tank car, inspection found the top threads on the assembly were broken and split. After a thorough inspection of the yard, the top assembly and the rupture disk was not located . SPSI personnel replaced the entire rupture disk assembly and decontaminated the tank car. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Freddie Hines 270-395-7121. The shipper will apply for an FRA Movement Approval prior to releasing the car for transportation.    This incident did require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non Conformance Report will be filled for this incident.    Cause Code: 424  NARRI - 5 x (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100

SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, and a CSX Hazardous Material Manager were dispatched to the scene and found the cause of the release was due to 4 loose liquid line mounting flange bolts/nuts and a deteriorated mounting flange gasket. column25: RPMG Inc. by KAAPA Ethanol LLC
column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Railroad Safety Inspector inspecting railcars in the railyard reported tank car UTLX 204372 leaking product from the base of the threaded 3 inch liquid valve. Intact shipper seal identified as KAAPA Ethanol 0000345 was removed from the valve housing cover during this inspection process. UTLX 204372 was carefully moved to and isolated at a repair track within the railyard. A response contractor was notified to inspect UTLX 204372 and mitigate the liquid valve leak. In the morning of 11/18/2011, UTLX 204372 was inspected by the response contractor. The 3 inch liquid valve was loose on its threaded connection by 1/8 of a turn. A small puddle of product at the base of the liquid valve that didn't evaporate was wiped. It was decided to remove the liquid valve to inspect the valve's threaded connection. Sealant found on the threaded connection was sparse and dry. The threaded connection was cleaned and Teflon thread tape applied with an overcoat of thread sealant compound. The liquid valve was reinstalled and properly tool tightened. As a precaution, the two inch threaded air valve  was removed, threads cleaned, new sealant tape and thread compound applied before reinserting and tool tightening the air valve. The valve housing cover was closed and seal TIS 5835 applied. Response was concluded by 1245 hrs. MST, 11/18/2011. The shipper was contacted and applied for a FRA OTMA for continued rail transportation of UTLX 204372.

column168: An unusual odor was reported in the railyard. Rail car inspections by BNSF contract responders resulted in the identification of residue tank car UTLX 58835 as the odor source. Further inspection of UTLX 58835 revealed that the odor was emanating from the vacuum relief valve (VRV). The VRV was removed and a pipe plug was inserted and tool tightened into the vacated VRV orifice. The odor quickly dissipated and ceased after response concluded by approximately 1610 hrs. CST, 11/20/2011.  Visual inspection of the removed VRV revealed that the VRV's weather cap under the stem nut was bent to one side which may indicate that the VRV valve stem was bent also. The VRV's O-ring at the stem base appeared pinched and misaligned. The shipper was notified and applied for a FRA OTMA for rail transport of UTLX 58835 to a qualified repair facility for furtherance.

United Vision Logistics truck (Mini-Float) was headed east on 4-lane divided highway.  A vehicle headed west in the east bound lane (headed the wrong way) contacted our United Vision Logistics truck head-on causing both vehicles to leave the roadway and came to rest on the opposite side of the road. Louisiana State Police HazMat was on scene along with Louisiana Department of Envrionmental Quality.  Louisiana State Police Right-to-Know was notified of the incident. column168: Quality Carriers Claim Number: 32028    On November 7, 2011, a Quality Carriers tractor tanker carrying UN1093 Acrylonitrile released approximately 15-20 gallons of material onto the asphalt parking lot at the Freight Liner Dealership located at 401 Daniel Payne Drive in Birmingham, AL. There were approximately 150-200 employess at the Freight Liner Dealership that were evacuated and taken to a safe zone. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor to the site to perform clean up operations and perform the necessary tanker transfer from the damaged tanker to a replacement tanker. The material leaked from a seem on the bottom of the tanker, which was collected with a pool that was set up underneath the tanker. Absorbent booms were placed around the tanker to secure any additional released material. The contractor utilized the proper PPE and transferred the material from the damaged tanker to a replacement tanker that was provided by Quality Carriers. The material was transferred into the replacement tanker successfully. All of the waste was collected and containerized and is pending disposal. No storm drains, waterways or soils were impacted as a result of this release.

column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: NATX 301863 was discovered to be leaking product from the bottom outlet valve.  The cap was in position and tool-tight with liquid leaking around the top edge.  The handle extension was in place on the valve operating shaft but was missing the attachment pin through the operating shaft.  The valve was verified to be closed (MGP seal #504985) and the cap was removed.  Product was observed being released past the bottom seal on the valve ball while the valve was closed.  In addition, two gaskets were present in the cap.  All of the bottom outlet valve nozzle flange bolts were verified to be tight.      The cap was reinstalled, temporarily stopping the release and the valve handle resecured and sealed (UPRR HAZMAT #97).  The car was spotted back into the plant and unloaded.  The shipper was responsible for obtaining a one-time movement approval to allow the car to proceed for repairs.  No active remediation was planned for this area as the alcohol evaporated.
column169: Ensure that no leaks are present following loading of the tank car.

DRIVER DROPPED R/FRONT STEER TIRE OFF PAVEMENT ONTO SOFT SHOULDER AT CURVE IN HIGHWAY, RESULTING IN ROLL-OVER OF TRACTOR AND TRAILER.  COMPANY OWNER AND SAFETY MANAGER TRAVELED TO SCENE AND ASSISTED AND WENT TO HOSPITAL TO CHECK ON DRIVER. OFFICE CALLED ENVIROTECH HAZMAT CLEANUP COMPANY TO SCENE, FOR CLEANUP OF SPILL. TRAILER HAD 2 HOLES ON RIGHT SIDE, BOTH 87010 INCHES IN LENGTH BY 4 TO 5 INCHES WIDE.  POLICE REPORT AND PHOTOS ATTACHED.
column169: WE USED AND DISCUSSED THIS ACCIDENT WITH ALL OUR DRIVERS IN SAFETY MEETING, NOVEMBER 11TH, 2011. THIS DISCUSSION INCLUDED THE DRIVER RESPONSIBLE FOR THIS ACCIDENT. WE DISCUSSED IMPROVING ATTENTIVE DRIVING, IN ORDER TO ELIMATE DROPPING RIGHT FRONT WHEEL OFF OF PAVEMENT.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: On November 30th, 2011, two flatrack trailers with a total of 1,600 palletized and stretch wrapped automotive batteries (UN 2794) each, reported by the shipper to be "drained" and "containing no hazardous residue", were delivered to the carrier of record's terminal. After further inspection, it was determined that these batteries still contained acid. The shipment was placed on hold by the carrier until the shipper can render the shipment compliant. The shipper arrived at the carrier's premises and provided a proper dangerous goods declaration and labeled and placarded the shipment appropriately. The shipment, now compliant, was subsequently transported without further delay. END OF REPORT
column169: Improve community outreach targeting both commercial shippers and non-commercial ("mom and pop" type) shippers. END

column168: At approximately 0305 Friday November 11, 2011 we received a emergency callout for offroad diesel.  Our driver was traveling west on Airline Hwy (Hwy 61) in Laplace when the driver of a 2005 Chevy Malibu decided to make a U-turn and side swiped our truck, hitting the passenger side steer tire through the fender, saddle tank, loading heads/ piping, and into the front drive tire.  The impact cracked two of the u-clamps on the #3 and #4 compartments spilling approximately 20 gallons of Diesel from the piping onto the Hwy and shoulder, sand was quickly delivered to contain the spill and absord Diesel.  The handle of the loading head cracked off with the collision preventing us from being able to drain the lines.  There was a slow leak for approximately 35 minutes.  After the State trooper inspected the Bobtail, he determined the leaks were stopped and the truck safe to drive.

column168: A yard hump job pulling rail cars in the railyard experienced a failed knuckle in their cut of cars which allowed several rail cars to roll-away from the cut colliding into another yard job that was stopped in the yard and unattended after the crew was safely moved from the area after being  warned of the impending collision. Included in the yard job that was struck was tank car ADMX 31033 that derailed on its side and sustained a compromising hole in the B-end tank head near the lower right quadrant. Product escaped from the breach until responders were able to plug the hole in the tank head by Noon PST on 11/07/2011.  An earthen dike was built to contain spillage. Pooled ground spillage was vacuumed, placed in portable frac tanks and earmarked for appropriated disposal. Air monitoring was initiated and no adverse conditions were recorded during the incident. The remaining product in ADMX 31033 was transferred into portable frac tanks and earmarked for reuse/recycling.

column168: 11/29/2011: 0915AM: Received call from Mechanical Department P. McWilliams, advising tank car GATX 34330, load Elevated Temperature Liquid NOS (a motor oil detergent), was noted to have released product, seemingly from the top, and was wet on both sides of the car.  Car leaks only under movement and is located on track #3 Receiving at Conrail's Oak Island Yard, Newark, NJ.  Car was isolated.    0930AM: At request of Conrail, emergency response contractor Hepaco-React responded to the site.  Inspection revealed 4 of 6 manway cover securement bolts not even hand tight; and the manway cover gasket was missing.  Compatible gasket replaced and manway cover resecured.  Contractor remediated/decontaminated the car (reporting approximately 1 gallon had spilled on the car) and treated an effected area on the ground immediately under the center of the car (approximately 1 pint).  Car okayed to move onto original destination.

On November 6, 2011, a Schneider National Bulk Carriers, Inc. tanker released approximately 1 gallon of UN3264 corrosive liquid onto an asphalt parking lot due to the tanker building pressure. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site for remediation. The product was transferred into a replacement tanker. Granular absorbents were applied to the impacted asphalt and the waste was containerized for disposal.

column168: 11/11/2011: At approximately 2:30PM, CR Trainmaster T. Gonzalez called to advise tank car GATX 69496, load, Fuel Oil, was reported leaking from the top of the car when car was under movement.  Car located at East End of #7 Receiving track at Oak Island Yard, Newark, NJ.  Car isolated for response.    CR A. Richter, Risk Manager, notified Hepaco-React (contract emergency response) to inspect and remediate the car.  Further inspection by Hepaco-React noted 1 of 8 manway cover securement bolts not applied; the remaining 7 of 8 manway cover securement bolts were not even hand tight; and, the manway cover gasket was deteriorated and in pieces.  Additionally, it was reported the air vlalve closure plug was not tool tight.    Compatible gasket replaced, manway cover and air valve made secure.  Approximately 10 gallons had sprayed out on the car (suspected when car was classified in yard and coupled with another car).  Due to cold weather, however, the product released solidified quickly.  Also reported approximately 1 pint on the ground under the car.  Car was completely decontaminated the following morning, 11/12/2011.  Small area on ground that was effected was cleaned and remediated during the initial inspection on 11/11/2011.  Car okayed to be forwarded to original destination.

column168: On Friday November 25, 2011 at approximately 15:45 we received a call that blood vials were found on the street at the intersection of Lower River Street & Oneida Street located directly up the block from our Plant.  Immediately after this notice we checked the most recent trailer that arrived which was from the Bronx Facility.  Upon opening the trailer door, there was a 17 gallon sharps container that fell causing the lid to break which spilled out numerous blood vials.  The inhouse clean up team then went up the block to clean up the blood vials that were reported.  In addition, the inhouse clean up team was instructed to go to the Quickway Gas Station located at 195 County Hwy 48 where the trailer last stopped to fuel.  Blood vials were also found and cleaned up at the Quickway Gas Station.  Following this the inhouse clean up team checked the roadways leading to the plant.  More blood vials were found and cleaned up at the I-88 overpass in Otsego.  In total 22-5ml blood vials were found and clean up.     During this time the Bronx inhouse clean up team was sent to check the roadways leading to I-87 which is the route taken to the Plant for any blood vials.  No blood vials were found, therefore this spill was an isolated event that took place between the Quickway Gas Station to the Plant in Otsego County.       The trailer which the spilled occurred from was also inspected for containment defect.  No issues were found; there were no holes or breach of containment and all locks/seals were in place and operational.
column169: All affected employees were retrained on proper load securement and use of racks for all sharps containers which would have prevented this situation from occurring.  The employee directly responsible for loading and securing the 17 gallon sharps container was suspended in addition to being retrained.  As an added precaution the trailer door seals will be replaced with larger seals to accommodate for normal door shifting during transportation.

Three transformers containing PCB contaminated oil were being transported by Freehold Cartage to Veolia's Port Washington WI facility to be transferred to another vehicle for the balance of the shipment to Phoenix AZ. Upon arrival it was discovered that the pallet the transformers were secured to collapsed and the strapping holding the transformers became loose. This allowed the transformers to tip side to side during transportion.  The shifting between the transformers loosened the lid and damaged the bushings attached to the transformer. This resulted in PCB contaminated oil spilling from the transformer. The vehicle being used to transport the transformers was equipped with a secondary containment system and all oil was confined to the secondary containment. Although contained the other packages in the shipment also became contaminated with PCB contaminated oil. These packages as well as the transport trailer had to be decontaminated prior to being released from the site. All containers and the vehicle were decontaminated in accordance with the EPA requirements for PCB contaminated oil spills. Contaminated material was added to the manifest and resumed shipment to Phoenix for final disposal in accordance with the PCB rules.
column169: Retrain employees on the proper handling methods when preparing PCB pole transformers for transportation including:    1.Package oil filled electrical equipment within secondary containment. The pole mount transformers contained on this shipment were small enough that they would fit inside a drum. By placing them inside the drum with floor dry to secure against movement, even if a leak occurs, the released material would not affect the transport vehicle or other containers.    2.For larger transformers and equipment, drain the equipment prior to shipment and transport the oil in appropriate drums.     3.Do not load transformers on pallets. Because of the amount of metal contained within the transformers the weight per square foot is typically higher than that of a standard drum. As such, a standard pallet will not support the weight of the transformer. Whenever possible load the transformers directly on the floor.    4.Ensure that the transformers are secured against movement while in transport.   5. Protect bushings and other projections on transformers from damage.

Clean Harbors Caribe, Inc. accepted a shipment of hazardous waste for transportation to a fully licensed waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at Clean Harbor’s in transit storage facility in order to consolidate less than truck load quantities onto a single transport vehicle for continued transportation.  While in storage pending continued transportation, an inspection of the containers identified that four (4) individual containers had failed allowing material to escape onto the floor of the trailer and asphalt dock area.  Facility personnel assembled a response team and after donning appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the trailer.  Upon further inspection, it was discovered that the 4 containers failed along a side seam.  The response team placed each of the 4 containers into suitable salvage containers and used a chemically compatible absorbent material to absorb all free liquids.  This material, along with materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into the salvage drums and are being monitored to insure additional pressure does not develop before the containers are placed back into transportation.
column169: At the time the containers were accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed.  It is believed that during storage, pressure built up in the containers causing the seam to fail.  We do not believe that pressure alone caused the containers to fail as the failure along the seam of each of the 4 containers appeared to be a non violent seam failure.  In order to prevent a recurrence, we are reviewing the waste stream to identify what may have caused the over pressurization and to take appropriate actions to insure continued transportation is incident free.  In addition, we have contacted the container manufacturer to inquire if they have received any similar reports of seam failures involving involving this type of containers.

column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: An operator failed to make proper preparations for transport. The top manway cover was not properly secured. The estimated time of release is between 15-30 minutes. The carrier stopped at a nearby truck stop to get a weight on the truck scales. At this time the spill had stopped. The driver observed the spilled product and contacted the facility. Facility personnel were immediately dispatched to the truck stop. While on route facility personnel found additional spillage on the roadway that leads to the truck stop, the fire department was contacted for assistance. Facility personnel contacted a contract clean up contractor. Decker Road was blocked off for cleaning activities. Clean up crew started cleaning an estimated 1 hour after notification. Once clean up was completed the roadway was opened back up up for vehicle traffic.
column169: The facility will provide additional training, update operating procedures for improved administrative controls. Physical controls will be enhanced to assist in proper preparation for transport activities.

CN Mechanical Department employee reported vapors coming from the top of tank car CGTX 18491 (L / ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES, LIQUID, N.O.S.) during switching operations at the CN Champaign Yard, Urbana, IL. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting the cap for a pipe mounted to the manway missing and the cap for the liquid line missing. Neither pipe had a valve on it which allowed liquid product to spill on the top and sides of the tank car and vapors to escape. Shipper's response contractor replaced the caps, scrapped the top and sides of the tank car to remove the product. Tank car released for movement.

While picking up rail cars at the CN Spaulding Yard, near Bartlett, Illinois, a CP Railway switch crew reported a strong  odor coming from tank car PROX 29991 (R/ Last contained: Ammonia, Anhydrous). All appropriate departments notified, car isolated in track. CN's response team responded, on arrival no seal was noted on the protective housing and an unused seal, CFL 232061 was found inside. Further investigation noted all three valve plugs less than tool tight, the B/end liquid and vapor valves opened slightly, allowing product vapors to escape. Valves and plugs properly secured, the protective housing sealed. Tank car released for movement to destination.

On 11/21/2011, MS DOT Inspector T. Thomas, noted excess product on the side of the tank car TAEX 297 (L/ Flammable Liquid, N.O.S.) while inspecting rail cars in the CN Jackson Yard, MS. All appropriate departments notified. Shipper's response contractor responded noting manway bolts less than tool tight and the manway gasket missing allowing product to be released during movement. New manway gasket installed and manway properly secured. Residue product was removed from the outside of the tank car, fixtures, handholds and ladders wiped down. Tank car was then released to destination.

FRA Hazardous Materials Inspector Mitchel Goetz noted fresh product on the sides and top of tank car GATX 22330(L / SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION) during a yard inspection at the CN Kirk Yard, Gary, IN. All appropriate departments notified, car isolated in track. All covers, housing and valve seals were noted intact. CN's response team responded noting two swing bolts down, two swing bolts less than tool tight and the manway gasket protruding out the side of the lid allowing product to escape during movement. Product was also noted on adjacent tank car UCLX 16325. Manway gasket replaced and manway was properly secured. Product neutralized, washed from both cars and they were released for movement to destination.

column168: JAMES MAUPIN A MARTIN TRANSPORT, INC. DRIVER WAS TRAVELING EAST ON FM 2067 APPROACHING HWY 183 IN GONZALES COUNTY, TEXAS. THIS IS A TEE INTERSECTION WITH STOP SIGN ON FM 2067. MR. MAUPIN WAS UNABLE TO COMPLETELY STOP AND TRIED TO MAKE RIGHT TURN, MOVEMENT OF LIQUID CAUSE TRAILER TO ROLLOVER AND SLIDE ON LEFT SIDE. TRAILER SLID OFF ROADWAY, CRASH BOX CAUGHT EDGE OF GRASS AND CAUSED TRAILER TO ROLL COMING TO REST ON RIGHT SIDE. MARTIN'S DISPATCH RECEIVED CALL OF ACCIDENT AND DISPATCH RESPONSE TEAM FROM CORPUS CHRISTI, TX, SAN ANTONIO, TX, AND BAYTOWN, TX. EMPTY TRAILER WAS ALSO DISPATCH TO SITE FOR TRANSFER. TRAILER WAS NOT LEAKING AFTER ROLLOVER. ONCE MARTIN PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON SIDE, TRANSFER OF PRODUCT WAS STARTED STILL NO LEAKS. REMOVED ABOUT 25 BBLS OF PRODUCT BEFORE LEVEL DROPPED BELOW INTERNAL VALVE. ONCE TRANSFER PUMP WAS STOP, A LEAK STARTED FROM VACUUM VALVE. KEEPING VACUUM ON TRAILER LEAK WAS STOPPED. FIVE GALLON BUCKETS WERE USED TO CONTAIN PRODUCT DURING REST OF TRANSFER UNTIL LIQUID LEVEL DROPPED BELOW VALVE LEVEL. DIRT AND W BAR SPRING MAYBE REASON FOR LEAK.

NARRATIVE:   On 11-23-2011, at approximately 08:45, a Loader began pressurizing railcar UTLX 130215. The connection between the railcar and the product fitting had a loose bolt which resulted in a release of approximately 3-4 gallons of product when the car started to pressurize. The product impacted the side of the railcar, the track ballast and blacktop. Lime was applied to neutralize the product. After neutralization the lime was placed in a bucket for proper disposal.  -    AWARENESS ITEM:   1. Both the Loader and Terminal Manager are unavailable to assist in the investigation.     2. The Loader was employed for approximately 3 months and has performed this transfer numerous times without incident.     3. At the time of the incident, the Loader complained of migraines.
column169: ROOT CAUSES:  1. During setup, the Loader failed to ensure the security of the railcar fittings.     CORRECTIVE ACTION:   1. Ensure all Loaders understand the requirement to make all connection tool tight.  Confirm this understanding with an Employee Demonstration Checklist.

column168: Claim Number: 32181    On November 22, 2011, a Quality Carriers tractor tanker carrying UN1268 Petroleum Distillates, NOS was involved in a single vehicle accident and rolled over on Highway 17 between Summersville and Mountain View, MO. ERTS dispatched an environmental crew to perform cleanup operations and to also perform a tanker transfer. Upon the environmental contractor's arrival it was reported that the local hazmat team had already began the tanker transfer. The environmental contractor assisted with the tanker transfer and reported that approximately 1 gallon of material was released from the dome lid on the damaged tanker. The tanker transfer was completed successfully. The environmental contractor hand excavated the area of contaminated soil that was affected by a 3 gallon diesel fuel release and containerized all of the waste for transportation and disposal. The wrecker service uprighted the tractor tanker and hauled it off site. The 1 gallon of material released from the tanker evaporated and no cleanup was necessary for that material released. No storm drains or waterways were impacted as a result of this release.

column17: United Transport of East Longmeadow, Inc.
column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  During offload, a break occurred in the fuel line, which resulted in the loss of approximately 10 gallons of fuel oil.  The fuel released to the asphalt surface and adjacent soils.  Enpro Services, Inc. of Burlington, Vermont was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, Enpro Services, Inc. applied speedy dry to the free liquid, and began hand excavating the impacted soils.  Fuel was contained to immediate area and did not threaten to impact waters of the state.  Spent speedy dry and contaminated soil were containerized into three (3) 55-gallon drums, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures as a result of the release.
column169: United Transport of East Longmeadow, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce driver safety and safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: The driver of the oil truck was traveling south on Md 244 when he said a deer ran out of the woods in front of him.The driver turned to miss the animal and his driver side wheels went off the pavement onto the soft shoulder. The driver tried to return the vehicle to the pavement for about 200 feet and when the vehicle got on the pavement again the load shifted and the vehicle rolled over on the passenger side cracking the seam of the cargo tank with a 3" long crack. The truck continued to roll over across a ditch and come to rest on it's driver's side. At this point the crack was at the top and only 21 gallons of fuel oil was released. When response personnel arrived the oil had stopped leaking and the crack was plugged. Hazmat Crews from St. Mary's County, Charles County, Pax River Naval Base responded. As well as MD State Police, St. Mary's Co. Sheriffs Dept., Md. Dept of the Environment, St. Highway and Burcn Oil's Response Team. In a joint effort by the response teams, 3 holes were cut in the cargo tank and the vehicle was pumped off. Recovery of the 21 gallons of lost oil had already began.The soil around the vehicle was removed and disposed of at the Calvert County Landfill. The area was declared free of oil by MDE on 12/1/11 Property damage to mailboxes was repaired on 12/1/11.

column168: On Nov. 2 2011 DAVE RIEGER, BURD BROTHERS DRIVER, WAS ATTEMPTING TO MAKE A DELIVERY TO MIAMI CORRECTIONAL FACILITY.  WHEN THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO MAKE THE DELIVERY OF 8 TOTE, ONE OF THE TOTES HAD FLIPPED ON ITS SIDE ON TOP OF A PALLET.  AS THE TRUCK WAS UNLOADED, ANOTHER TOTE WAS DEISCOVERED TO HAVE "BLOWN TOP".  THE FORK LIFT OPERATOR UNLOADED THE FIRST TOTE THAT WAS LAYING ON ITS SIDE, AND MOVED IT OUT INTO THE GRAVEL PARKING LOT. THE FORK LIFT OPERATER ATTEMPTED TO GET THE TOTE STANDING UPRIGHT AND RAN THE FORKS THROUGH THE TOP PART OF THE TOTE ALLOWING AN UNKNOWN QUANTITY OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL O FHYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION TO ESCAPE ONTO THE PARKING LOT.  THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR DID MANAGE TO GET THE TOTE UPRIGHT.  FOR THE OTHER DAMAGED TOTE, MIAMI CORRECTIONAL FACILITY HAD AN EMPTY TOTE THAT FORMAELY HELD THE SAME CHEMICAL , HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION AS THE TOTE WITH THE "BLOWN TOP".  DAVE RIEGER WAS ABLE TO SECURE A CLAMP AND HOSE FITTING TO ATTACH TO THE TOTE.  THEY MANANGED TO GET THE TOTE TO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK AND LET GRAVITY DRAIN THE TOTE INTO THTE EMPTY TOTE THAT WAS USED FROM THE FACILITY.   AS FOR THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS THAT HAD ESCAPED ONTO THE PARKING LOT, AN EMPLOYEE OF MIAMI CORRECTIONAL FACILITY, GRABBED THE GARDEN HOSE AND SPRAYING THE AREA SUCH THAT THE WATER AND SOLUTION WAS WASHED OVER INTO THE GRASS.  TH E2 DAMAGED TOTES AND THE TRANSFER TOTE WERE RETURNED TO CHEMICALS, INC. ON NOVEMBER 3 2011.
column169: AFTER SPEAKING WITH BURD BROTHERS DOCK CREW, WE FOUND OUT THAT THE TOTES WERE LOADED AND STRAPS AND SKID SPACERS WERE USED.  HOWEVER, THERE WAS ONLY ONE SKID SPACE USED.  BURD BROTHERS POLICY IS TO USE A MINIMUM OF 5 SKIDS OR HALF THE HEIGHT OF A TOTE WHEN USING SKID SPACERS.  THIS WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THE TOTE FROM FLIPPING ON ITS SIDE.. AS FAR AS THE STAP GIVING AWAY, WE FELT IT WOULD BE BETTER TO STAY WITH SKID SPACERS WHEN SPREADING OUT A LOAD, INSTEAD OF USIN THE STRAPS AS WELL.  HOWEVER, IN LIGHT OF USIN A "FALSE WALL" IT IS RECOMMENDED TO USE A MINIMUM OF 2 STRAPS AT THE SAME SPOT TO GIVE ADDITIONAL STRENGTH AND AS A "BACKUP".  IN SPEAKING/INTERVIEW THE DRIVER, WE FEEL THE DRIVER DID A GOOD JOB OF AVOIDING THE ACCIDENT GIVEN THE SITUATION.  EVEN SPOKE WITH A WITNESS ABOUT THE EVENTS WHO CONFIRMED DRIVERS SEQUENCE OF EVENTS.  ASK THE DRIVER IF THERE IS ANYTHING HE COULD/WOULD HAVE DONE DIFFERENTLY NOW IN HINDSIGHT, THAT WHEN THE OTHER DRIVER CAME ALONG SIDE AT A HIGH RATE OF SPEED, HE SHOULD HAVE BECOME MORE OF A DEFENSIVE DRIVER AND BACKED DOWN ON HIS SPEED GIVEN HE WAS GOING THE SPEED LIMIT,  ESPECIALLY COMING ON UP ON THE RAILROAD AREA AND TO BE MRE AWARE OF SURROUNDING AREAS AND POTENTIAL FOR SITUATJIONS.  AS FOR THE RELEASE OF HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION ON THE GRAVEL. SPEAKING WITH THE DRIVER, THE FORKLIF OPERATOR HAD TAKEN THE TOTE INTO THE GRAVEL PARKING LOT. AS THE DRIVER WAS INSIDE THE TRUCK ASSESSING THE DAMAGE TO THE FREIGHT, UNBEKNOWNST TO HIM, THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS TRYING TO UPRIGHT THE TOTE. TOLD THE DRDIVE RHE NEEDS TO CONTROLTHE ACCIDENT SCENE AND TO MAKE SURE THINGS ARE ASSESSED AD RISK ARE EVALUATED BEFORE PROCEEDING WITH ANY TYPE OF CORRECTIVE MEASURE BEFORE PROPER PEOPLE ARE NOTIFIED.

column168: RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM FCI DRIVER THAT HE WAS IN A SINGLE VEHICLE ACCIDENT. (NO OTHER PARTIES INVOLVED) WHILE NEGOTIATING A LEFT BEND ON THE HIGHWAY THE LOAD APPEARED TO HAVE SHIFTED RESULTING IN TRACTOR & TRAILER ROLLING ONTO ITS PASSENGER SIDE. THE CONDITION OF THE ROADWAY WAS SLIPPERY DUE TO RAIN.  THE 2 ROLL OFF CONTAINERS LANDED ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY, CONTENTS WERE PARTIALLY SCATTERED ALONG SHOULDER. TRACTOR & TRAILER CAME TO REST IN LEFT LANE. AT THIS TIME AUTHORITIES HAD NOT BEEN NOTIFIED SO MY INITIAL PHONE CALL WAS TO 911. I IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWED WITH A CALL TO THE PA DEP HOTLINE/NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. UPON ARRIVAL OF THE STATE POLICE I WAS INFORMED THAT BRESSLER GARAGE & NORTH RIDGE GROUP WERE CONTRACTED TO REMOVE VEHICLE AND CLEAN UP ANY DEBRIS DIRECTLY ON INTERSTATE. THE STATE POLICE GRANTED FCI PERMISSION TO CONTRACT BOLIS TO HANDLE THE REMOVAL OF DAMAGED CONTAINERS & ANY ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP OF ASBESTOS RELEASED ALONG THE SHOULDER OF THE INTERSTATE. FCI OPERATIONS MANAGER DISPATCHED 2 VEHICLES WITH 3 EMPTY CONTAINERS TO ASSIST. BOLIS TRANSFERRED CONTENTS OF LOADS ALONG WITH DEBRIS INTO 3 ROLL OFF CONTAINERS. THE 3 LOADED CONTAINERS WERE REMOVED BY FCI DRIVERS AND RETURNED TO OUR DUNMORE PA TERMINAL. DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO JERSEY SHORE HOSPITAL AS A PRECAUTION. HE WAS ALSO ISSUED A POST ACCIDENT DRUG/ALCOHOL TEST IN ACCORDANCE WITH FMCSA, RESULTS WERE NEGATIVE.
column169: THE STATE POLICE DETERMINED THAT THE DRIVER WAS NOT SPEEDING NOR DRIVING IN A RECKLESS MANOR THEREFORE NO TICKETS WERE ISSUED. WITNESS ACCOUNTS CONFIRM THIS DECISION. OUR INTERNAL INVESTIGATION CONCLUDED THAT 3 DECIDING FACTORS LEAD TO THIS ACCIDENT. THE LOAD CONTENTS SHIFTED, THE DRIVER DID NOT PROPERLY SECURE ROLL OFF CONTAINERS, AND THE ROADWAY WAS SLIPPERY DUE TO RAIN. HOWEVER, ALTHOUGH THE LOAD MAY HAVE BEEN SLIGHTLY TOP HEAVY AND THE ROADWAY SLIPPERY, IT'S THE DEIVER'S RESPONSIBILITY TO DETERMINE IF IT'S SAFE TO TRANSPORT AND TAKE ADDED PRECAUTIONS TO PROPERLY SECURE THE LOAD. AS A CORRECTIVE MEASURE ALL DRIVERS WERE RETRAINED & FURTHER EDUCATED ON PROPER LOAD SECUREMENT AND SAFE DRIVING TACTICS. AS AN ADDED SAFETY MEASURE ALL ROLL OFF DRIVERS ARE NOW REQUIRED TO USE STRAPS AS WELL AS CHAINS TO FURTHER SECURE CONTAINERS FOR TRANSPORT.

column168: On October 19, 2011, a dumpster used for metal recycling was transported from the Naughton Plant to Basin Industries, a metal recycler.  Upon unloading it was discovered that a sealed tote, containing approximately 20 - 25 gallons of a solution, had accidentally been placed in the dumpster.  Basin immediately notified PacifiCorp of the misplaced sealed tote.  Upon hearing of the tote, PacifiCorp contacted Veolia ES Technical Services to verify the contents of the tote and have it transported back to Naughton.  PacifiCorp determined on November 29, 2011, that the tote contained 32% HCL inhibited acid 2600.  On December 14, 2011 Veolia transported the sealed tote back to the Naughton Plant where the acid would be used for PH control.  No leakage or spillage occurred during this event.

column168: OUR DRIVER (#1) WAS TRAVELING WEST ON HWY. 101. HE WAS COMING UP TO THE INTERSECTION OF OLD GARDINER ROAD. HE SAW VEHICLE #2 STOPPED ON OLD GARDINER ROAD TO HIS RIGHT FACING THE STOP SIGN. OUR DRIVER CONTINUED DRIVING AT 55 MPH. AS OUR DRIVER STARTED TO PASS OLD GARDINER ROAD. #2 SUDDENLY PULLED INTO OUR DRIVER'S LANE. OUR DRIVER HAD NO TIME TO MANEUVER OR AVOID HITTING #1. OUR TRAILER BOUNCED OFF #2'S VEHICLE, VEERED TO THE LEFT IN THE EASTBOUND LANE. OUR TRACTOR AND FRONT TRAILER FLIPPED ONTO ITS SIDE DOWN THE EMBANKMENT, THE TRAILER REMAINED UPRIGHT. #2'S VEHICLE FLIPPED AND ROLLED DOWN THE EMBANKMENT LANDING ON ITS ROOF ON OLD GARDINER ROAD.  OUR DRIVER NOTIFIED OUR CENTRAL DISPATCH; CENTRAL DISPATCH NOTIFIED OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATORS, WHO NOTIFIED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM. THE WA STATE PATROL AND NRC WERE ON SCENE. THERE WAS NO PRODUCT LOSS, ONLY MINOR INJURY SUSTAINED TO THE DRIVER IN VEHICLE #2. OUR DRIVER AND TRAINEE DRIVER SUSTAINED NO INJURIES OTHER THAN SORE MUSCLES. OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM ASSISTED IN THE SAFE PUMP OFF OF 8004 GALLONS OF REGULAR UNLEADED GASOLINE AND 3,301 GALLONS OF PREMIUM UNLEADED GASOLINE FROM OUR TRACTOR AND TRAILER; THE PRODUCT WAS DELIVERED TO THE CUSTOMER. THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE TOWED AWAY FROM THE SCENE AS WAS VEHICLE #2.

column168: Ceres driver was operating a 3500 gal fuel truck. He failed to yeild at the stop sign pulling out in front of an on coming tractor trailer traveling at estimated 60mph. The other driver had little time to react hitting our fuel truck in the right front side of the cab and fuel tank. The impact ruptured the chassis fuel tank and also the side of the 3500 gal tank. The force of the impact knocked the 3500 gal tank off of the chassis. At this point both trucks expolded into flames. Both vehicle proceeded of the roadway into the adjacent corn field. Our chassis appeared to have rolled once while the tank that was knocked off appeared to have rolled 3 times.splashing fuel all around. The entire semi tractor, our chassis and the tank were all completely engulfed in fire.   The right front compartment appeared to have been ripped open from the colision, however with the aluminum construction several areas of the tank had melted due to the intense heat of the fire.   3 locals fire depts. responded extinguishing the fire which took about 45 min.then Fire dept then placed absorbent materials on any remaing fuel that was on the ground. The cargo tank still had 1300 gallons of fuel that was contained in it after the fire was extinguished. ERS environmental services was called to the scene to do the clean-up.
column169: Since there were no witnesses we do not know the exact reason why our driver pulled out in front of on coming traffic.   Packageing, securement, HOS or the vehicle did not contribute to the accident. it was driver error. unknown reason.

column168: TRUCK WAS IN ROUTE TO MAKE DELIVERIES IN THE LOCAL OIL & GAS FIELD. THE DRIVER COULD SEE AN ACCIDENT AHEAD ON THE COUNTY ROAD. THE ROAD WAS COVERED WITH SNOW AND ICE. THE DRIVER BEGAN TO SLOW DOWN AND AS THE TRUCK ALMOST CAME TO A STOP, IT BROKE TRACTION AND BEGAN TO SLIDE FROM THE HIGH SIDE OF THE "SUPER" IN THE ROAD. THE TRUCK SLID ACROSS THE ROAD UNTIL IT HIT THE OPPOSITE SHOULDER. UPONE HITTING THE SOFT SHOULDER, THE TRUCK TURNED OVER ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE AND ROLLED DOWN AN EMBANKMENT COMING TO REST BACK ON IT WHEELS. THE TRUCK MADE ONE COMPLETE REVOLUTION. DURING THE ROLLOVER, THE TANKER SPLIT OPEN ON ONE OF THE WELDED SEEMS. THIS SPLIT REMAINED ON THE HIGH SIDE OF THE TANKER WHEN IT CAME TO REST. THIS RESULTED IN FUEL BEING LOST DURING THE ROLLOVER BUT NOT AFTERWARD.  THE PIPING ON THE TANK SUFFERED EXTENSIVE DAMAGE ALSO, BUT THE FIRE VALVES, VENTS AND MANHOLES FUNCTIONED PERFECTLY NOT LEAKING ANY PRODUCT. A TOTAL OF 85 GALLONS WAS LOST. THE REMAINING FUEL WAS PUMPED INTO ANOTHER TRUCK.
column169: DRIVER DID NOT RECEIVE ANY CITATION. ACCIDENT CONSIDERED TRUE "ACCIDENT". EQUIPMENT ON TRUCK WORKED AS DESIGNED. NO SUGGESTIONS.

column168: The cause of the spill resulted from fuel being released during transfer operations using a truck-mounted pump.  The system is set up so that fuel can be discharged on either the driver or passenger side of the tanker truck through a T-shaped pipe.  The fuel was being transferred to a 10,000-gallon aboveground tank on the driver's side but the operator failed to close off the proper valve on the passenger side piping.  The pressure built up in the line and eventually forced the end cap off the pipe resulting in the release.  Overall, the cause of the releae was due to human error.    The following corrective actions took place immediately after the release occurred: The release was contained within a confined area using on site sand placed with a front end loader.  The free product was then pumped into four 55-gallon drums using a small portable pump and absorbent was used to soak up the remainder of the free product not absorbed into the soil.  These corrective actions took place on Monday, November 21, 2011.  The contaminated soil was excavated by Papco, Inc.'s subcontractor (Tidewater Utility)on Tuesday, November 22, 2012 and seven dump truck loads of contaminated soil were removed and properly disposed of at Clearfield MMC on that same day.  The Virginia Department of Environmental Quality's Tidewater office visted the site and on November 28, 2011 approved the clean-up with no further actions required.
column169: The corrective actions taken to help prevent recurrences of this situation include the follwoing:  The fuel delivery employee has been counseled on what he did wrong and has been disciplined.  The issue was thorughly discussed at the Papaco driver safety meeting to insure that future repeat occurrences do not happen.  The fuel delivery company (Papco)has been supplied with Titan's SPCC Plan for this site that stipulates procedures to be followed during fuel unloading operations.

column168: Summery:  Dave Palmer received a call from John Miller regarding a product spill at the Olinda  Lease in Brea California. Reported amount of release was one barrel.    Cause:  Driver Wayne Mingo while loading light crude violated company policy when he entered his cab and reported to us that he fell asleep. Mr. Mingo failed to monitor his loading as required. Root cause, driver error.    Response and Recovery:  Chris Pace and a crew arrived and started the clean up process. A vacuum truck was obtained from Breitbum and our crew started pressure washing the asphalt parking lot in the area. Patriot Environmental sent a rep to the location for evaluation of this process.    Although the parking area was cleaned the following day I went along with John Miller to view the area. I was noted that a small amount of product had sipped into a creek bed, it was also determined that this creek had natural seepage and we could not determine new contamination and old contamination. A meeting was scheduled  for Friday with environmental specialist and Breitbum Management to discussfurther clean up requirements.    The following is a list of who attendant this meeting.    •Dave Palmer- Pan Pacific Petroleum  •  Don Stewart- Pan Pacific Petroleum  •  Dale -Patriot Environmental  •  Edward Quinones- Production Foreman Breitburn  •  Michael Joseph- Environmental Health & Safety Breitburn  •  Brian Jngallinera- Environmental Services City of Brea  •  Donald Barkley- Barkley Environmental Engineering Services  •  Cory Kong- Environmental Scientist Department ofFish & Game     It was detennined  that the creek had previous contamination prior to our spill. Recommendations from the Department ofFish & Game was that we remove a small area of contaminated soil leading to the creek and surrounding area. Also noted was vegetation around the berm that containing over-spray from the pressure washing needed to be removed, mainly consisting to fallen leaves and dead grass.    Patriot Environmental preformed this cleanup and the area was cleared by Fish and Game at 1500. Pending issue with Breitburn Management is what to do about the stained asphalt? Dave asked from them to call when a decision was made.    * NOTE ON CREEK BED, IT COULD NOT BE DETERMINED THAT OUR SPILL MADE IT INTO THIS CREEK. THIS AREA HAD PRE-EXISTING CONTAMINATION DUE TO NATURAL SEEPAGE OF OIL IN THE AREA.
column169: Recommendations:    Driver was charged with failing to follow proper pump procedures. Mr. Mingo will be  terminated for his actions. Safety meeting was scheduled the following day to discuss this accident and review our loading and unloading procedures.    COMPANY LOOKING INTO SPILL CONTROL/PRESENTATION SYSTEMS SUCH AS TITAN AND SCULLY GROUND HOG UNITS. THESE SYSTEMS ALLOW MONITORING OF LOADING TO PREVENT HUMAN ERROR.

column168: On November 21, 2011 Apex was notified by Pilot Travel Centers, LLC of a surface release of diesel fuel at the above referenced facility.  During a regularly scheduled fuel drop, an estimated 20 gallons of diesel fuel was released to the ground surface in the vicinity of the facilities diesel fuel aboveground storage tank.  Facility personnel responded to the release by applying 25 bags of Oil-Dri absorbent to the ground surface.  Apex mobilized to the site to remove the Oil-Dri and excavate any additional impacted material identified from the release.  The Oil-Dri was removed and placed in two 55-gallon steel drums for proper disposal.  Apex used a skid steer loader to remove impacted soil and gravel from the site and the adjoining Roanoke Cement Plant property.  All excavated material was placed in four 55-gallon steel drums.  Apex returned to the site on November 22, 2011 and repaired the excavated areas with clean stone.  All impacted materials were removed from the site on November 23, 2011 and transported under non-hazardous waste manifest for disposal by Environmental Options, Inc. of Rocky Mount, Virginia.

On November 7, 2011 at approximately 6:05pm, a CRCT driver started unloading crude oil from his trailer and prior to completion of the process noticed crude oil coming out of a valve on the passenger side of the trailer.  The driver immediately turned off the pump and shut the discharge valve and then contacted the Bartlesville Office Dispatch Supervisor.   Upon release notification, at approximately 6:25 pm, CRCT response personnel were immediately mobilized to the site with containment boom, absorbent boom, boat, 2 vacuum trucks, 1 transport truck/trailer, and a backhoe.  After initial assessment (approximately 7:40pm) CRCT response personnel strategically placed containment and absorbent boom on the dry unnamed creek approximately 50’ downstream of pooled crude oil. Response personnel began to utilize vacuum trucks to remove the free crude oil from the pooled areas within the otherwise dry unnamed creek bed.  Response personnel also began constructing an underflow dam to prepare for an impending rain event forecast for the area.  At the time of the initial response there was no water in the unnamed creek.  As the bulk of free oil was being removed from the pooled areas the rain event began causing water to flow down the unnamed creek.  Due to the excessive downpour during the rain event, the underflow dam and containment boom washed out allowing an estimated five (5) barrels of unrecovered crude oil to be washed downstream towards Skiatook Lake.  CRCT immediately called the National Response Center (at 9:25pm) when it was apparent that the release would ultimately reach Skiatook Lake.  ACME Products Company was also contacted to assist in the response.  ACME arrived on-site at approximately 10:00pm and began to survey the lake for access areas for additional containment boom placement.  A containment boom was placed across the cove where the unnamed creek entered Skiatook Lake.  Response efforts in the following days concentrated on recovering crude oil from behind the boom across the cove and cleaning up the oily debris along the unnamed creek.   Recovery efforts were essentially completed by November 23, 2011.  Absorbent booms and pads and the downstream containment boom were left in place until December 21, 2011 to address any residual oil. During the week of January 1st, 2012 the United States Army Corp. of Engineers (USACE) and Bureau of Indian Affairs (BIA) conducted an inspection of the affected area and documented that clean-up efforts had been completed to their satisfaction.    The information above was previously provided to USEPA in response to a Clean Water Act, Section 308 Information Request.

column168: Monday, November 21, 2011  Between 6:00-6:30 PM GRAINCO FS, Inc. employee finished machine fill of equipment for KR & G Excavating. He exited the site on Center Point Street. He proceeded to turn left on Mississippi Street and a hose that connects the tank belly valve to the pump came off the pump.  Diesel fuel began to flow onto the road.    The drive was unaware of the leak. He turned North on Baseline Road then West on Arsenal Road. When turning left on Arsenal the driver could see the fuel discharge and immediately pulled over on the Arsenal Road shoulder. He exited the cab and shut off the belly valve to stop the release.    He immediately called another GRAINCO FS fuel driver.  He then called Operations Manager and then Risk and Regulatory Manager.    Will County Highway Department to spread sand on Mississippi Street and Baseline Road.    Jim Snyder, Energy Department Manager and Bill Stahler went to the scene arriving approximately at 8:30PM.  We met with Brian from Will County HAZMAT, Elwood Fire Depariment Lieutenant, Will County Highway Department and Jim Clark, IEPA Emergency Response.  After about one hour of discussions IEPA was satisfied that we could respond the following morning in the light to start clean up.  We could  not obtain any more sand as the officials declared the emergency over.  Our only contact, D Construction, was having a party and did not have anyone available to respond.    Tuesday, November 22, 2011  Jim Snyder, Bill Stahler and Mark Tuttle, Energy Services responded to the scene at approximately 7:30 AM. they placed fuel absorbent booms and pillows at two storm drains at the corner of Mississippi Street and Baseline Road. Also, booms and pillows were placed at the Arsenal Road shoulder.     D Construction was contacted and a street sweeper arrived to sweep sand spread the prior night by Will County Highway. In addition, sand was spread and swept twice along Mississppi Street on Tuesday AM by D Construction

column168: TRUCK-TRAILER WAS LOADED TRAVELING SOUTH ON THE I-40E OFF RAMP ONTO US 220S. AS TRUCK APPROACHED MIDDLE OF RAMP THE DRIVER NOTICED AN ABANDONED VEHICLE OFF THE RAMP ON THE RIGHT SIDE.  THE DRIVER OVER STEERED/CORRECTED CAUSING THE TRACTOR-TRAILER TO JACKKNIFE AND ROLL COMPLETELY OVER TWICE COMING TO REST IN CENTER OF US220 AGAINST MEDIAN BARRIER.  AS TRUCK-TRAILER ROLLED, THE FRONT LEFT SIDE OF TRAILER SPLIT VERTICALLY UP THE SHELL 2-3 FEET, CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 1200 GALLONS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (GASOHOL) TO ESCAPE.    DRIVER WAS ABLE TO CLIMB OUT OF WRECKAGE AND BEGIN DIRECTING TRAFFIC AWAY FROM THE INCIDENT.  THE DRIVER ALSO CONTACTED DISPATCH WHO IN TURN CONTACTED A HAZMAT TEAM AND LOCAL AUTHORITIES.  LOCAL AUTHORITES ARRIVED ON SCENE FIRST.  THE AREA WAS SEALED AND CONTAINMENT OF SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ACHIEVED BY FIRE DEPARTMENT USING NECESSARY ABSORBENT MATERIALS.  HAZMAT CREWS ARRIVED AND BEGAN FURTHER CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN UP PROCEDURES THAT INCLUDED BUT NOT LIMITED TO FOAM APPLICATION, PLACEMENT OF ABSORBENT BOOMS IN ADJACENT STORM DRAIN AND WATERWAY AND THE EVENTUAL REMOVAL AND REPLACEMENT OF SOIL AND ROCK. RECENT TESTING HAS CONFIRMED NO FURTHER ACTION NECESSARY.

column169: Recommendations would not take the form of mechanical improvements, but that of public awareness training. Commercials using various media forms to enhance the general public awareness about commercial vehicles in general and hazmat carriers specifically would help road safety.  Our children are educated in drivers education classes, an emphasis could be place on one chapter concerning commercial motor vehicles. A precedence for this type of training has already been set through the Trucking Associations called the TACT program, educating the public about cutting off trucks who are trying to maintain a safe following distance on the highway.  Public awareness needs enhancement about the dangers of commercial vehicles on the highway and how to avoid these hazards.

PRIOR TO DELIVERY, DRIVER NOTIFIED CUSTOMER OF GAUGE READING, CUSTOMER RELAYED GAUGE WAS WORKING INTERMITENLY, BUT APPROPRIATE CAPACITY OF DELIVERY  WOULD BE ACCOMODATED IN CUSTOMER TANK.  DRIVER THEN BEGAN TO FILL TANK, DRIVER THEN NOTICED LIQUID COMING OUT OF CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK AND IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE OFFLOAD PROCESS AND CALLED DISPATCHED TO REPORT INCIDENT. CUSTOMER PERSONNEL OPERATOR WAS ON SIRE DUSRING THE OFFLOAD WITH DRIVER, OPERATOR ON SITE NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR OF INCIDENT.  DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS APPROXIMATELY 3 MINUTES.  MITIGATING THE RELEASE WAS BY IMMEDIATELY STOPPING THE OFFLOAD PROCESS EMERGENCY REMOTE ON EQUIPMENT. THEN POWERING DOWN EQUIPMENT TO INVESTIGATE WHERE RELEASE ORIGINATED AND OCCURRED FROM.
column169: RECOMMENDATIONS MADE WERE TO:    IMMEDIATELY REPLACE LEVEL GAUGE ON STORAGE TANK AND PROVIDE CUSTOMER WITH INSTRUCTIONS ON REPLACING FAULTY GAUGE AND TESTING THE GAUGE CAPACITY ACCORDING TO SPECIFICATION PROVIDED BY VENDOR OF GAUGE. PERIODIC TESTING OF GAUGE WAS ALSO RECOMMENDED AS WELL AS AN ADEQUATE MAINTENANCE PROGRAM FOR ALL PARTS LOCATED ON STORAGE TANKS ON SITE.  OPERATING PROCEDURES SHOULD BE IN PLACE FOR QUARTERLY AUDIT OF SUCH EQUIPMENT, AND THAT THIS QUARTERLY INSPECTION BE DOCUMENTED AND KEPT AT LOCATION OF INSPECTION.

This was two shipments from Underground Computers of Jenison, Ml. Shipment numbers 5435737351 (GRR-Sheung/Sheung Shui HK) & 543514256T moving from GRR - Cheng Shui NT HK. These shipments were routed to Chicago (ORD) for further forwarding to Hong Kong (HKG) via UPS Airlines (5X).Initial transport was via ground service to the ORD Gateway. The shipper (Computers Underground) notified UPS at GRR that their shipment to HKG may contain Lithium batteries. At that point, an effort to intercept these two shipments was initiated. SN#: 543514256T was intercepted at Chicago (ORD) and is currently being held there. Shipment 5435737351 had already departed for HKG on UPS Flight 5X104. Shipment 5435737351 is currently being held at the UPS facility at HKG. Points of Contact:  Photographs of these shipments are attached to this report.
